    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-08-11T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-08-11T11:00:00-05:00" n="617"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d617">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">817.51/2171: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Minister in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hanna</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-08-11T12:00:00-04:00"
                            >August 11, 1930—noon</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>81. Legation’s 100, August 9, 3 p.m. The Department’s views were stated to Dr.
                    Carazo by telephone to New York practically verbatim as set forth in the second
                    paragraph of its telegraphic instruction No. 80, August 8, 5 p.m.</p>
                <p>The Department of course is unable to say in what manner Dr. Carazo will report
                    this statement to President Moncada. He was, <pb facs="0769" n="675"
                        xml:id="pg_675"/> however, informed that the views conveyed to him had been
                    telegraphed to you. You may, therefore, if you deem it necessary, take such
                    steps as appear desirable to prevent President Moncada from misunderstanding the
                    Department’s attitude.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Carr</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
